@NODE "FKT-DERIVE"
@TITLE "derive()"
@NEXT "FKT-DET"
@PREV "FKT-COUNT"
@TOC "Functions"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual -------------------------------------------------- derive() -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Functions" "derive()"
@{U}derive()@{UU}

@{B}sypnosis:@{UB}
   @{B}derive(@{I}ex @{UI},@{I}var @{UI},[@{I}n @{UI}])@{UB}

@{B}arguments:@{UB}
   @{I}ex @{UI}: any expression
   @{I}var @{UI}: identifier
   @{I}n @{UI}: positive integer (default is 1

@{B}result:@{UB}
   depends on the type of @{I}ex @{UI}

   This will calculate the @{I}n @{UI}-th (partial) derivation of the expression @{I}ex @{UI}.

   Some examples:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f'(x) = derive(x^2, x)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(x) = x^2
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f'(x) = derive(f)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f'(x) = derive(f(x), x)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(x, y) = x^2 + y^3
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f_x'(x, y) = derive(f(x,y), x)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f_y'(x, y) = derive(f(x,y), y)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} g(x) = derive(f(x,1), x)

   If you use @{I}derive () @{UI} as a 'stand alone' expression (that means not as the
right side of an function definition)  and the used variables are not  defined
in this context, then they are created  as constant objects. This can lead  to
errors, if the same name was used earlier but with another type, e.g.:
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} x=[1,2,3]
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} ...
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} f(x)=sin(x)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} derive(f(x), x)

   You should then declare @{I}x @{UI} as a constant before you use @{I}derive () @{UI}, but you
should prefer a construction like

                          @{I}f'(x) = derive (f(x), x) @{UI}


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ę by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
