@REM KEY 0 0 "Functions" "plot_repfunc()"
@{U}plot_repfunc()@{UU}

@{B}sypnosis:@{UB}
   @{B}plot_repfunc(@{I}handle @{UI}, @{I}n @{UI}, @{I}f @{UI})@{UB} (not implemented)
   @{B}plot_repfunc(@{I}handle @{UI}, @{I}n @{UI}, @{I}f @{UI}, @{I}x @{UI})@{UB}
   @{B}plot_repfunc(@{I}handle @{UI}, @{I}n @{UI}, @{I}f @{UI}, @{I}x @{UI}, @{I}t @{UI})@{UB}

@{B}arguments:@{UB}
   @{I}handle @{UI}: plotter handle
   @{I}n @{UI}: positive integer
   @{I}f @{UI}: any expression
   @{I}x, t @{UI}: identifier

@{B}result:@{UB}
   number

   Replace the @{I}n @{UI}-th function of the plotter referenced by @{I}handle @{UI} by the sup-
plied function @{I}f @{UI}. If the plotter have less than @{I}n @{UI} functions, @{I}plot_repfunc  @{UI}
just works like @{"plot_addfunc()" LINK "FKT-PLOT-ADDFUNC"}.

   @{I}x @{UI} and @{I}t @{UI} (if supplied) are used as variables. If @{I}handle @{UI} refers to an ani-
mated plotter,  you  should  supply  @{I}t @{UI};  otherwise  the  function  cannot be
animated. For not animated plotters, supplying  @{I}t @{UI} is useless and usually  re-
sults in a not plotable function.

   @{I}plot_repfunc  @{UI} returns the index of the inserted function (1 for the first
function, 2 for the second, etc.).


